ttish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bussey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk, of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy, France: Boucé in Orne, from which came Robert de Buci mentioned in Domesday Book, Bouce (Manche), or Bucy-le-Long (Aisne). All are named with a Latin personal name <i>Buccius</i> (presumably a derivative of <i>bucca</i> ‘mouth’) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","English: variant of   Boosey  .","Americanized form of German   Busse  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessey","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): perhaps a variant of   Bussey  .","French: habitational name from any of the places in Côte-d'Or and Loire named Bessey, from the Gallo-Roman estate <i>Bassiacum</i>, from the Roman personal name <i>Bassius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."]},{"name":"Boosey","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>bosy</i> ‘ox-stall, cow-stall’ (Old English <i>bōsig</i>)."]},{"name":"Bussie","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bussey  , of Norman origin. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bucey","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Bussey  ."]},{"name":"Busey","meanings":["English: variant of   Bussey  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Bussey was born about 1115, in Old Warden, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William I de Busli, was 51 and his mother, Hawise Espec, was 52. He had at least 1 daughter with Rohese FitzGilbert. He died in 1165, in Essendine, Rutland, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"Abt. 1115–1163":"umbes 1115–1165","1085–1135":"1085–1135","1115–1165":"1115–1165","1130–1185":"1130–1185","1115–1166":"1115–1166","1145–1195":"1145–1195","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1154–Male":"1154–Surnud","–1182":"–1182","1065–1115":"1065–1115","1065–1122":"1065–1122","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","1065":"1065","1163":"1165","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1085":"1085","1182":"1182","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","Abt. 1115":"umbes 1115","1145":"1145","1122":"1122","1166":"1166","about 1145":"umbes 1145","BY 1122":"1122","Old Warden, Bedfordshire, England":"Old Warden, Bedfordshire, England","Bourne, Lincolnshire, England":"Bourne, Lincolnshire, England","Essendine, Rutland, England":"Essendine, Rutland, England","Burton Agnes, Yorkshire, England":"Burton Agnes, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt. 1115–1163":"noin 1115–1165","1085–1135":"1085–1135","1115–1165":"1115–1165","1130–1185":"1130–1185","1115–1166":"1115–1166","1145–1195":"1145–1195","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1154–Male":"1154–Kuollut","–1182":"–1182","1065–1115":"1065–1115","1065–1122":"1065–1122","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","1065":"1065","1163":"1165","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1085":"1085","1182":"1182","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","Abt. 1115":"noin 1115","1145":"1145","1122":"1122","1166":"1166","about 1145":"noin 1145",